PyExp

Target IP: 192.168.167.118

Scanning



There are only two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and MySQL. I was expecting at least HTTP open.

Enumeration

Port 3306: MySQL
From the scans above, I know the host is running Linux. And root is a common user to have for MySQL application. Looks like this is the only entry point as we have to bruteforce.


And this turned out to be successful as I was able to bruteforce the password of root. I have the credentials root:prettywoman now.


Using the credentials above, I have access to the MySQL application. There is an interesting database called data. This data database contains a table called fernet. And this table contains two columns: cred, and keyy.
Cred: gAAAAABfMbX0bqWJTTdHKUYYG9U5Y6JGCpgEiLqmYIVlWB7t8gvsuayfhLOO_cHnJQF1_ibv14si1MbL7Dgt9Odk8mKHAXLhyHZplax0v02MMzh_z_eI7ys=
keyy: UJ5_V_b-TWKKyzlErA96f-9aEnQEfdjFbRKt8ULjdV0=.


After trying to decode those strings above, I had no luck. I tried converting it to different bases, decoding using CyberChef, etc. But I typed the name fernet on Google and found this is an application! By providing the cred and keyy, I cracked it! The decoded message is shown above at line one. There is only one other application left: SSH. Maybe the credentials will work against this application?

Exploitation


And now I have a foothold on the machine as lucy using the credentials from enumeration section.

Privilege Escalation


Looks like we can gain a root shell by exploiting this Python script.


And bingo. We now have a root shell.
